If you bought Lyft at the opening day high of $88.60 in twelve trading days you have now lost 37% of your investment. If you got shares at the IPO price of $72 you are down 22%. This does not happen in healthy markets and bodes ill for all Unicorn IPOs.  
@paranoidbull

First off, will the IPO happen before 1 Oct 2019? According to all the news (and Uber hasn't denied it), they filed their S-1 form with the SEC in the week of 3-7 Dec 2018. I tried to find other reasons to file an S-1 other than going public, but I wasn't able to find any. I wasn't able to find any examples of companies that filed an S-1 but did not subsequently IPO --- maybe I didn't Google the right things. It would be interesting to hear from someone who knows more here. Then I looked through past intervals between S-1 filings and IPOs, for tech companies specifically --- both recent IPOs, and big IPOs. Thus I found that, of 10 companies: * 6 had 30 or fewer days between S-1 and IPO
   Snap in 2017; SolarWinds, Anaplan, Dropbox, Eventbrite, DocuSign in 2018;
* Tencent Music took 70 days in 2018;
* Facebook took 107 days in 2012;
* Google took 112 days in 2004;
* Alibaba took 136 days in 2014. There have been ~25 non-govt-shutdown days since the S-1, and there are ~230 days between now and 1 Oct 2019, plus the . So it seems all but certain that Uber will IPO before then, say 6% chance it doesn't --- 5% chance for not IPOing at all (because of, to me, "unknown unknowns"), and 1% for it getting very delayed. The question now is, what will be the market cap. Apparently Uber was last (implicitly) valued at ~$75B by Toyota in Aug 2018, when it invested $500M in it [1]. So it seems unlikely that the IPO price will be less than that --- otherwise, wouldn't Toyota just wait for it? Let's call <$70B a 10% chance, and $40B a 0% --- I think they'd sooner give up on IPOing than fetch such a small amount. The other number that is floating around these days is $120B, which you can find mentioned in many news sources. However, people more familiar with the matter seem to think that's high [2]. Some other people seem to think $90B is more plausible due to "stock market slump" [3], but that article is from early Jan 2019, and the S&P500 is ~12% higher now than it was then, so if we do a simple linear extrapolation we get $100B. All in all it seems to make the >$130B bucket unlikely. But Uber is a household name; could enough retail investors buy to cause a significant rise in the price? According to a few minutes of Googling, retail investors own anywhere between 5% and 20% of all stocks. Since the stock market is valued at ~$30T-$40T, that means retail investors have conservatively $1.5T invested. So if 10% of them put 10% of what they have on Uber, that's over $15B, which seems like enough to move the price. But, will retail investors massively act on IPO day? Intuitively it seems like most wouldn't even know the exact date. All in all I want to call >$130B a 10% chance. That leaves 74% to split between the $70B-$100B and $100B-$130B ranges; I don't know enough to tell them apart, especially since it seems like around ~$100B is a plausible value. So I'll just give them both equal odds, 37%. [1] http://fortune.com/2018/08/27/toyota-investment-uber-worth/
[2] https://techcrunch.com/2019/01/07/ubers-ipo-may-not-be-as-eye-popping-as-we-expected/
[3] https://www.theinformation.com/articles/ubers-confidential-documents-show-path-to-90-billion-ipo
